---
description: Translating Joe's feedback into spec edits
alwaysApply: false
---

Feedback maps to spec edits by slide `id`; rebuild produces a NEW version
(old files stay untouched). Common translations:

- "make slide N punchier" → rewrite title as a sharper assertion; cut bullets
  to ≤3; consider promoting the key number to `big_number` or adding a
  `highlight:` to the chart.
- "too busy / too much text" → split into two slides, or move detail to
  `notes:`; check the ~40-word ceiling.
- "make it pop / more visual" → replace `content` with `big_number`,
  `icon_row`, `comparison`, `timeline`, or `chart` per the slide-type
  catalog; add `animate: build` where sequencing helps.
- "the numbers changed / change 18 to 19" → edit the value in the spec,
  rebuild. Mention Joe can also right-click → Edit Data directly in
  PowerPoint (his charts are live).
- "add a slide about X" → insert with a fresh `id`; ids never shift, so
  later feedback stays unambiguous.
- "tone it down" → set `animate: none` / `deck.animations: off`; swap quote
  or big_number drama for content/table restraint.
- Ambiguous feedback (two plausible readings) → ask Joe, don't guess.

If Joe hand-edited an output version in PowerPoint: that file is his. Ask
before regenerating the slides he touched, and fold his wording back into
the spec so the next rebuild keeps it.
